Author::::girlhalfempty
DateTime::::2016-03-11T13:59:47Z
Hello there. As others here have advised, please seek support from your mother's GP or from Alcohol Advice Services in your area. Most Alcohol support services will be able to advise you on various ways of bringing the topic up in a gentle and supportive manner with her. Many services also provide support for family members of people struggling with drink issues. On another important note, if your mum is consuming 15 units per evening, there is a very strong likelihood that she is physically dependent on alcohol - in fact, if this is the case, she does "need" the alcohol to ward off withdrawals. Tell-tale signs of alcohol withdrawal include things such as tremors, sweats, increased anxiety, and nausea/sickness.Alcohol withdrawal can be very distressing and potentially dangerous - in some cases it can result in withdrawal-induced seizures and possibly death. Please, for your mum's safety and well-being, do not ask her to stop "cold turkey" or even reduce significantly without the proper support! Good luck!



Author::::Theresathing
DateTime::::2016-03-11T13:39:21Z
Your mother has an alcohol addiction, whatever else is going on in her life. Unless she attends to this, she will find it almost impossible to sort any other problems out. Please explain this to her and tell her that there is a lot that can be offered in support but that she is the one who will have to take ownership of this problem. Suggest that she sees her GP, as she may already have physical damage as a result of her drinking. She must not suddenly drinking, but come off it in a controlled manner, and will need the help of a health professional for this.



